Name: Artopolis Bakery
Summary: Artopolis serves a massive array of baked goods, along with some of the strongest coffee we’ve ever had. As soon as you walk into the bakery, which is located in a strip mall in northern Astoria, you’re hit with smells from the kitchen that will make you want to consume as many of these desserts as possible, immediately. They specialize in sweet and savory Greek pastries, like galaktoboureko, which is basically custard on flaky phyllo dough. As for the coffee, it’s similar to Turkish coffee, which if you’re not familiar, is very strong.

Name: Queens Comfort
Summary: We specialize in regional American food, nostalgia & fun.

Name: Gussy's Bar & Grille
Summary: Live Music every Friday & Saturday,Great Hospitality,Beer and Spirits.

Name: Kurry Qulture
Summary: Awarded the "2017, 2019 Best Indian Restaurant In Queens" (Best of Boro), Kurry Qulture is NYC's first Indian restaurant to feature a seasonal menu. Located on the bustling 30th Avenue in Astoria, Queens, Kurry Qulture elevates the Indian dining experience with surprising-creative cuisine and attentive service in a chic yet casual ambience. Owner, Sonny Solomon, brings over 15 years of experience at some of NYC's most notable fine dining establishments. Since opening in November, 2015, Kurry Qulture has been featured in numerous publications including Michelin Guide 2017, Eater NY, Boro Magazine, Epoch Times, AM NY and by several local foodie bloggers. Five star online reviews rave about the cuisine and attentive commitment to the experience of every guest.

Name: Monika's Cafe Bar
Summary:
Established in 1996.

A former carpet warehouse transformed into a hearty, bohemian, electric space that provides nourishment for the soul and belly. Read more about us in a August 1997 article in the New York Times written by Charlie LeDuff 'Artists Arrive. Cafes, of Course, Follow . . .', "in the southern section of the neighborhood bounded by Broadway and 37th Avenue and 31st and Steinway Streets. They have not just arrived from overseas but from over the East River. They are the hipsters, the serious artists, the writers, the nouveau Manhattan Bohemes and our lovers on the velvet couch... '''People have gotten tired of living in the belly of the beast,''" said Monica Constantinides, a 32-year-old native of Cyprus...Anchored by the Kaufman Studios, the American Museum of the Moving Image and their thousands of actors and artisans, the neighborhood has become an economically viable place to make business, make art and make a life."

Name: Embers Steakhouse
Summary: Brooklyn's Best Steak value since 1985. Quality Dry Aged meats grilled to perfection together with succulent seafood and classic cocktails in a warm setting with attentive and proffesional service.

Name: Standard Burger

Name: Calaca
Summary: Mexican food from the North Pacific coast of Mexico (Sinaloa)

Name: Colador Cafe
Summary: Are you hungry in Brooklyn? Welcome to Colador Cafe, where you can find great Sandwiches food available for delivery or takeout. Check out our online menu and place an order from our site. Don’t want to order now? Visit us at 1000 Bedford Ave.

Name: Kleinberg’s
Summary: "A neighborhood joint with local Brooklyn fare. Restaurant & Greenhouse & Bar."

Name: Building on Bond
Summary: Eclectically decorated with animal skulls and LPs, the neighborhood hang serves a cozy café menu.

Name: Regular Visitors
Summary: Regular Visitors is a corner store with homewares, a newsstand, a coffee counter, and apothecary.  A collaboration between Neil Rasmus of Izola, and Jesse James, founder and Creative Director of Aesthetic Movement, alongside the Aesthetic Movement design team, reimagined the former bike shop into Regular Visitors. The store is located in Boerum Hill, Brooklyn, and started trading last November, 2016.

Name: Cranberry’s
Summary: Casual standby offering coffee, breakfast bites, sandwiches & other quick eats, plus baked goods.

Name: Jack The Horse Tavern
Summary: Oysters plus hot & cold small plates served in cozy digs next door to parent Jack the Horse Tavern.

Name: 983 Bushwicks Living Room
Summary: Hearty New American dishes & some Mexican & Italian eats in a cozy spot with local art on the walls.

Name: The Awkward Scone
Summary:
The Awkward Scone is a queer- and woman-owned bakery and herbal tea cafe in Brooklyn.
Specializing in housemade herbal tea blends and pastries with coffee from Stumptown Coffee, tea
from Brooklyn Tea and featuring rotating local artists

Name: Brooklyn Cider House
Summary: Sagardotegi meets Bushwick: Brooklyn's first cider house styled after traditional Basque Sagardotegis (cider houses) with a full-scale cidery, tasting room, bar, and restaurant. Our fully-immersive cider experience is a four-course prix-fixe menu, with cider catching directly from ancient Asturian barrels. Our bar serves our ciders as well as ciders, beer, and wine from other New York farm-based producers and offers New American pub fare all day and brunch on the weekends.
